                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d821">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">821.76/6–2844: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Colombia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lane</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bogotá</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-06-28T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >June 28, 1944—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 29—2 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1152. Stations HJBB Cúcuta and HJED Cali have been monitored by trustworthy local
                    testing facilities and have been found to be <pb facs="0869" n="855"
                        xml:id="pg_855"/> operating on their respective assigned frequencies.
                    Colombian Ministry of Posts and Telegraphs has made similar test and makes the
                    same official report to Embassy. Local testing facilities suggest interference
                    with station AT&amp;T may be caused by All America station HKY now transmitting
                    on 4834 kilocycles; also that the two British stations mentioned in Department’s
                    telegram number 539 of June 20, 6 p.m. may be fading off their frequencies and
                    thus experiencing interference.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lane</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
